I mean, there's been
lots of opportunities

00:36:59.800 --> 00:37:01.175
to transactionalize it.

00:37:01.175 --> 00:37:03.300
People are like, well,
we're going to sell tickets.

00:37:03.300 --> 00:37:04.383
We can maybe sell tickets.

00:37:04.383 --> 00:37:06.970
Or insurance companies-- do
you want to partner with us?

00:37:06.970 --> 00:37:11.580
And what a great way to
sell some life insurance.

00:37:11.580 --> 00:37:13.710
Sure.

00:37:13.710 --> 00:37:14.250
No.

00:37:14.250 --> 00:37:17.143
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:17.970 --> 00:37:23.720
The thing about
transactions is that they

00:37:23.720 --> 00:37:26.130
don't necessarily,
by their design,

00:37:26.130 --> 00:37:28.230
bring people closer together.

00:37:28.230 --> 00:37:30.200
That's not the nature
of a transaction.

00:37:30.200 --> 00:37:32.510
A transaction
intentionally creates

00:37:32.510 --> 00:37:34.040
a little bit of a boundary.

00:37:34.040 --> 00:37:35.539
You know what you're
getting for it.

00:37:35.539 --> 00:37:37.492
Somebody knows what
they're giving you.

00:37:37.492 --> 00:37:38.450
That's great and clear.

00:37:38.450 --> 00:37:41.230
Gifts are messier.

00:37:41.230 --> 00:37:42.740
They're more human.

00:37:42.740 --> 00:37:50.660
Gifts are intended to
obligate people in some way.

00:37:50.660 --> 00:37:53.170
Warring tribes would
give each other gifts

00:37:53.170 --> 00:37:55.700
as this way of obligation.

00:37:55.700 --> 00:37:59.180
Gifts stay in some
level of circulation.

00:37:59.180 --> 00:38:01.220
That's kind of just their DNA.

00:38:01.220 --> 00:38:02.390
There's a DNA of a gift.

00:38:02.390 --> 00:38:04.370
And there's a DNA
of a transaction.

00:38:04.370 --> 00:38:06.380
Lewis Hyde writes about
this really brilliantly.

00:38:06.380 --> 00:38:12.170
And he was one of the people
who inspired Lessig and the--

00:38:12.170 --> 00:38:16.970
what's the open source that
