with the Cleveland
Clinic and probably 1,000

00:39:24.960 --> 00:39:26.790
medical partners.

00:39:26.790 --> 00:39:28.830
And I'm lecturing
at Sloan Kettering

00:39:28.830 --> 00:39:30.390
and partnering with
Sloan Kettering.

00:39:30.390 --> 00:39:33.090
So in about a
month, we've entered

00:39:33.090 --> 00:39:35.390
into the oncology space,
the terminal illness

00:39:35.390 --> 00:39:38.400
space, which would not let
you into this conversation.

00:39:38.400 --> 00:39:40.374
Death and cancer?

00:39:40.374 --> 00:39:41.790
They're just not
in the same room.

00:39:41.790 --> 00:39:43.310
We're going to beat cancer.

00:39:43.310 --> 00:39:46.290
And I was like, the
elephant is in the room.

00:39:46.290 --> 00:39:48.900
People who have a stage four
terminal diagnosis-- they

00:39:48.900 --> 00:39:51.120
are thinking about the
fact that they might die.

00:39:51.120 --> 00:39:54.060
Let's give them the
opportunity to talk about it.

00:39:54.060 --> 00:39:56.430
And I got a big
no for many years.

00:39:56.430 --> 00:39:58.620
And now I'm getting,
what a great idea.

00:39:58.620 --> 00:40:00.310
Where have you been
our whole lives?

00:40:00.310 --> 00:40:01.997
It's like, OK, yes.

00:40:01.997 --> 00:40:02.580
It's changing.

00:40:05.110 --> 00:40:07.290
But for me to be
able to get access

00:40:07.290 --> 00:40:11.760
to work with the Cleveland
Clinic and Sloan Kettering,

00:40:11.760 --> 00:40:13.830
it had to be a gift.

00:40:13.830 --> 00:40:17.104
If I was an entrepreneur
who had this idea,

00:40:17.104 --> 00:40:18.270
we wouldn't be sitting here.

00:40:18.270 --> 00:40:19.831
And there wouldn't be a book.

00:40:19.831 --> 00:40:21.830
DAVID LEVIN: You talked
about sending that email

00:40:21.830 --> 00:40:22.650
to 20 of your friends.

00:40:22.650 --> 00:40:24.335
I think at one point you had
this time when you sent out

00:40:24.335 --> 00:40:25.830
an email to a lot
of your friends.

00:40:25.830 --> 00:40:29.790
It resulted in you attending
your own funeral, I think.

00:40:29.790 --> 00:40:31.980
Can you tell us a little
bit more about that?

00:40:31.980 --> 00:40:32.730
How did it happen?

00:40:32.730 --> 00:40:33.521
MICHAEL HEBB: Yeah.

00:40:33.521 --> 00:40:35.530
Careful what you ask for.

00:40:35.530 --> 00:40:40.590
So I had just broken up with the
love of my life, so I thought.

00:40:40.590 --> 00:40:43.930
And I was really depressed.

00:40:43.930 --> 00:40:46.890
And I was about to turn 40.

00:40:46.890 --> 00:40:49.810
And the first thing
I thought was,

00:40:49.810 --> 00:40:51.930
I'm going to be alone
on my 40th birthday.

00:40:51.930 --> 00:40:53.716
And here's this great reckoning.

00:40:53.716 --> 00:40:55.590
And I'm going to think
about what a failure I

00:40:55.590 --> 00:40:57.987
am romantically.

00:40:57.987 --> 00:40:59.070
And I'm going to be alone.

00:40:59.070 --> 00:41:03.120
And so I sent out an
email to about 50 friends

00:41:03.120 --> 00:41:06.829
saying, hey, in two
months I'm turning 40.

00:41:06.829 --> 00:41:08.370
I don't know where
we're going to be.

00:41:08.370 --> 00:41:10.050
But I'm going to be somewhere
in the northern coast

00:41:10.050 --> 00:41:10.830
of California.

00:41:10.830 --> 00:41:11.640
Save the date.

00:41:11.640 --> 00:41:12.840
Tell me if you can come now.

00:41:12.840 --> 00:41:14.210
I need to know.

00:41:14.210 --> 00:41:16.680
And I got 40 yeses.

00:41:16.680 --> 00:41:17.630
I'll be there.

00:41:17.630 --> 00:41:19.350
Immediately I was
like, whew, I'm not

00:41:19.350 --> 00:41:21.930
going to be alone on my 40th.

00:41:21.930 --> 00:41:26.050
And then about a week
later, a friend--

00:41:26.050 --> 00:41:29.830
because now there's this list
with all of these people on it.

00:41:29.830 --> 00:41:34.230
Even though I was like, don't
reply all, he breaks that rule

00:41:34.230 --> 00:41:38.290
and says, hey, so Mr.
Death is turning 40.

00:41:38.290 --> 00:41:41.970
Let's go ahead and
celebrate his great turn

00:41:41.970 --> 00:41:45.120
by throwing him
a living funeral.

00:41:45.120 --> 00:41:52.020
And at that point, somebody has
called out an amazing challenge

00:41:52.020 --> 00:41:53.880
to me in front of everybody.

00:41:53.880 --> 00:41:55.931
And I can't be like,
that's a terrible idea.

00:41:55.931 --> 00:41:57.180
I actually was broken hearted.

00:41:57.180 --> 00:41:58.263
That's why I'm doing this.

00:41:58.263 --> 00:42:00.790
And now I have to die.

00:42:00.790 --> 00:42:02.100
And so I was like, great.

00:42:02.100 --> 00:42:02.670
Yes.

00:42:02.670 --> 00:42:04.530
Yeah, of course.

00:42:04.530 --> 00:42:05.130
We'll do it.

00:42:05.130 --> 00:42:07.800
And it got really serious.

00:42:07.800 --> 00:42:10.590
It really built up
steam as it got closer.

00:42:10.590 --> 00:42:12.390
And it turned into
the centerpiece

00:42:12.390 --> 00:42:16.800
of this long weekend and a whole
day dedicated to preparations.

00:42:16.800 --> 00:42:19.020
I ended up being
ritually bathed,

00:42:19.020 --> 00:42:21.870
anointed with oils,
dressed in white,

00:42:21.870 --> 00:42:25.640
brought downstairs
with my eyes closed.

00:42:25.640 --> 00:42:31.020
I actually was blindfolded
downstairs into this courtyard.

00:42:31.020 --> 00:42:33.930
And before I know
it, I'm being helped

00:42:33.930 --> 00:42:37.710
into what I then
realized just by texture

00:42:37.710 --> 00:42:43.110
and smell was my own
coffin and then picked up

00:42:43.110 --> 00:42:47.520
by pallbearers whose breath
smelled like whiskey.

00:42:47.520 --> 00:42:50.970
It's funny-- the little details,
the whiskey on their breath.

00:42:50.970 --> 00:42:56.400
I was like, I'm definitely at
my own funeral slash Irish wake.

00:42:56.400 --> 00:42:58.710
And they're drinking
because they're

00:42:58.710 --> 00:43:00.720
having a really hard time.

00:43:00.720 --> 00:43:04.260
They're not drinking because
they're day drinkers.

00:43:04.260 --> 00:43:06.892
They're drinking
because they're dealing

00:43:06.892 --> 00:43:08.850
with what looks like one
of their best friend's

00:43:08.850 --> 00:43:10.230
bodies in a coffin.

00:43:10.230 --> 00:43:13.260
And the whole thing makes
them incredibly uncomfortable.

00:43:13.260 --> 00:43:16.620
And so I get lifted
into this darkened room.

00:43:16.620 --> 00:43:17.880
It has one candle.

00:43:17.880 --> 00:43:20.040
And there's like
40 people in it.

00:43:20.040 --> 00:43:21.080
And a friend of mine--

00:43:21.080 --> 00:43:22.580
I didn't know who
it was at the time

00:43:22.580 --> 00:43:25.280
because I couldn't
recognize by her wailing--

00:43:25.280 --> 00:43:29.510
starts losing it in the way
that you might pay somebody

00:43:29.510 --> 00:43:31.380
to cry at your funeral--

00:43:31.380 --> 00:43:33.800
[? keeners, ?] which is still
a thing all over the world.

00:43:33.800 --> 00:43:35.950
You can pay someone to cry.

00:43:35.950 --> 00:43:39.140
And what it helps is other
people have the emotion.

00:43:39.140 --> 00:43:40.250
But I wasn't paying her.

00:43:40.250 --> 00:43:41.480
And she couldn't control it.

00:43:41.480 --> 00:43:43.340
And it was this
incredible woman, Alex,

00:43:43.340 --> 00:43:47.270
who just started wailing,
sobbing uncontrollably.

00:43:47.270 --> 00:43:50.090
And then it was very clear
that this was not a joke.

00:43:50.090 --> 00:43:52.424
Anybody who was still
kind of tongue in cheek--

00:43:52.424 --> 00:43:54.590
I mean, there might have
been some people there that

00:43:54.590 --> 00:43:56.990
had ingested some psilocybin.

00:43:56.990 --> 00:44:00.200
But that probably just made
it even more intense for them.

00:44:00.200 --> 00:44:05.750
I wasn't ingesting psilocybin
that day, just so we're clear.

00:44:05.750 --> 00:44:09.470
And so I'm laying
in this coffin.

00:44:09.470 --> 00:44:16.070
And for three hours, my
friends air their grievances--

00:44:16.070 --> 00:44:18.190
real grievances--
as if I were dead.

00:44:18.190 --> 00:44:21.830
I was like, I can hear you--

00:44:21.830 --> 00:44:24.660
really where I had failed them.

00:44:24.660 --> 00:44:29.060
But then the harder part
was where they loved me.

00:44:29.060 --> 00:44:31.010
I got to hear this.

00:44:31.010 --> 00:44:33.080
And I couldn't do
anything about it--

00:44:33.080 --> 00:44:37.010
40 people that mean the most to
in your life feeling like they

00:44:37.010 --> 00:44:40.850
can tell you in an unabashed
way how they feel about you

00:44:40.850 --> 00:44:42.760
without you being
able to deflect it,

00:44:42.760 --> 00:44:46.010
without you being able to
acknowledge them, nothing.

00:44:46.010 --> 00:44:47.480
I couldn't take it.

00:44:47.480 --> 00:44:49.130
And it made me
really uncomfortable.

00:44:49.130 --> 00:44:52.160
And my 15-year-old
daughter was there.

00:44:52.160 --> 00:44:54.710
And she got up on
the edge of my coffin

00:44:54.710 --> 00:44:56.180
and started talking to me.

00:44:56.180 --> 00:44:58.350
You want to have an
emotional experience?

00:44:58.350 --> 00:45:01.299
Have your 15-year-old daughter
attend your own funeral

00:45:01.299 --> 00:45:02.090
while you're awake.

00:45:02.090 --> 00:45:06.480
And so ultimately, my
takeaways from it--

00:45:06.480 --> 00:45:09.440
and so we created this
whole site, The Living Wake,

00:45:09.440 --> 00:45:12.380
so that people, again, can
have a blameable resource

00:45:12.380 --> 00:45:14.150
to throw these things.

00:45:14.150 --> 00:45:15.400
Because a lot of people--

00:45:15.400 --> 00:45:18.630
they're 80 or 90, or they
just want to play Tom Sawyer--

00:45:18.630 --> 00:45:20.640
want to have these experiences.

00:45:20.640 --> 00:45:23.030
But they don't want to be
the person that comes up

00:45:23.030 --> 00:45:24.530
with the idea and organizes it.

00:45:24.530 --> 00:45:29.600
So livewake.com we produced
just for, again, a gift.

00:45:29.600 --> 00:45:31.880
But what I realized
from that experience

00:45:31.880 --> 00:45:34.342
is I don't know how
to receive love.

00:45:34.342 --> 00:45:36.690
I got really good at giving it.

00:45:36.690 --> 00:45:40.550
And then I also in
research about how we die--

00:45:40.550 --> 00:45:42.980
there is an incredible
book called "How We Die."

00:45:42.980 --> 00:45:48.410
And I learned that the
heart is essentially

00:45:48.410 --> 00:45:50.370
two muscles on a timer.

00:45:50.370 --> 00:45:52.850
It's two distinct organs.

00:45:52.850 --> 00:45:56.230
One of those organs
receives blood.

00:45:56.230 --> 00:45:58.340
It's what it does all
day, receiving blood,

00:45:58.340 --> 00:46:00.050
oxygenating it.

00:46:00.050 --> 00:46:03.159
And then the other half of
our heart distributes blood.

00:46:03.159 --> 00:46:03.950
That's all it does.

00:46:03.950 --> 00:46:05.930
It just pumps blood all day.

00:46:05.930 --> 00:46:07.625
And then the timer--

00:46:07.625 --> 00:46:10.340
so you get pump pump, pump pump.

00:46:10.340 --> 00:46:12.380
Receive, give, receive,
give, receive, give.

00:46:12.380 --> 00:46:14.510
And a heart attack,
which is still

00:46:14.510 --> 00:46:16.760
the number-one
killer in the world,

00:46:16.760 --> 00:46:19.040
is an imbalance between
give and receive.

00:46:19.040 --> 00:46:21.250
It's an imbalance in that heart.

00:46:21.250 --> 00:46:22.220
The timing is off.

00:46:22.220 --> 00:46:24.980
And I was like, OK, so
if I don't figure out

00:46:24.980 --> 00:46:28.690
this side of my heart
that's receiving,

00:46:28.690 --> 00:46:31.880
then I'm reducing my
lifespan, reducing

00:46:31.880 --> 00:46:35.340
how much I can actually give if
I don't learn how to receive.

00:46:35.340 --> 00:46:36.570
And I'm going to die sooner.

00:46:36.570 --> 00:46:39.380
And so I got it
really hard that I

00:46:39.380 --> 00:46:41.730
needed to learn how to
slow down and receive,

00:46:41.730 --> 00:46:44.386
a pretty good lesson.

00:46:44.386 --> 00:46:46.010
DAVID LEVIN: You have
a ritual that you

00:46:46.010 --> 00:46:47.510
begin these things
with and a ritual

00:46:47.510 --> 00:46:49.100
that you end them with as well.

00:46:49.100 --> 00:46:52.220
At the end, I think you
have a ritual that everybody

00:46:52.220 --> 00:46:55.250
says something that they really
appreciate about the person

00:46:55.250 --> 00:46:56.840
to the side of them.

00:46:56.840 --> 00:46:58.100
And so I guess I'll end.

00:46:58.100 --> 00:47:00.750
And I'll say something that
I appreciate about you.

00:47:00.750 --> 00:47:02.880
Thank you so much for
coming here to talk to us.

00:47:02.880 --> 00:47:05.150
And thank you for covering
this important topic,

00:47:05.150 --> 00:47:08.840
spending the time to think about
important questions that can

00:47:08.840 --> 00:47:10.640
help us learn more about life.

00:47:10.640 --> 00:47:13.190
You have a quote in the
book from Kyoko Mori

00:47:13.190 --> 00:47:15.530
that says, "everything
we say about death

00:47:15.530 --> 00:47:17.270
is actually about life."

00:47:17.270 --> 00:47:20.362
And I feel like the questions
you have in here really

00:47:20.362 --> 00:47:22.070
help us to think about
our life and think

00:47:22.070 --> 00:47:23.310
about what's important.

00:47:23.310 --> 00:47:24.590
Thank you very much
for coming here today.

00:47:24.590 --> 00:47:24.890
MICHAEL HEBB: Yeah.

00:47:24.890 --> 00:47:25.931
It's an honor to be here.

00:47:25.931 --> 00:47:28.540
[APPLAUSE]

